---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="About — MeshTexas"
  description="Why and how MeshTexas runs its Texas MeshCore broker and analyzer, and how other regional mesh communities can get involved."
>
  <div class="page-intro">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h1>About MeshTexas</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">MeshTexas started as a way to make sense of a Texas-based <a href="https://meshcore.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MeshCore</a> mesh network — one place to see which nodes are active, how packets are moving across the state, and how the network is growing over time. Off-grid, decentralized mesh networking only gets more useful the more people can see it working, so instead of keeping that data to ourselves, we built a public map and opened it up.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="about-section tint">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>MeshCore <strong>observer nodes</strong> across Texas — devices configured to capture and forward live packet data — report to a self-hosted MQTT broker, which feeds a real-time analyzer and map. Everything runs on infrastructure we manage, is scoped to Texas-region nodes only, and is free for the community to use and watch.</p>
        <p>Setting one up takes a bit of configuration — not every node needs this, it's a dedicated observer role — but we've written guides for the most common hardware and software combinations. See the <a href="/connect">Connect</a> section for setup instructions covering MeshCore firmware, <code>meshcoretomqtt</code>, and <code>meshcore-packet-capture</code>.</p>
        <p>Regions are tagged using IATA airport codes (e.g. <code>SAT</code> for San Antonio, <code>AUS</code> for Austin) — not because they're airport-specific, just a compact, already-familiar convention for naming Texas metro areas without inventing new abbreviations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section coverage" id="coverage">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Coverage Regions</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">MeshTexas is active across Texas. Coverage grows as more operators add nodes and repeaters. IATA city codes are used to identify regions on the network.</p>
      <div class="regions">
        <div class="region active">
          <div class="region-code">SAT</div>
          <div class="region-name">San Antonio</div>
          <div class="region-status">Active</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">AUS</div>
          <div class="region-name">Austin</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">HOU</div>
          <div class="region-name">Houston</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">DFW</div>
          <div class="region-name">Dallas–Fort Worth</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">ELP</div>
          <div class="region-name">El Paso</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">ABI</div>
          <div class="region-name">Abilene</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">AMA</div>
          <div class="region-name">Amarillo</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">MFE</div>
          <div class="region-name">McAllen</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">SJT</div>
          <div class="region-name">San Angelo</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">TXK</div>
          <div class="region-name">Texarkana</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">CRP</div>
          <div class="region-name">Corpus Christi</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
        <div class="region">
          <div class="region-code">ACT</div>
          <div class="region-name">Waco</div>
          <div class="region-status">Growing</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section community tint" id="community">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Texas Mesh Community</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">Other Texas mesh radio communities and resources.</p>
      <div class="community-links">
        <a href="https://stxradio.com/stxmesh/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="community-card">
          <span class="community-name">STX Mesh</span>
          <span class="community-desc">South Texas mesh community — San Antonio and surrounding areas.</span>
          <span class="community-url">stxradio.com/stxmesh ↗</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://www.austinmesh.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="community-card">
          <span class="community-name">Austin Mesh</span>
          <span class="community-desc">Community mesh network covering greater Austin, Cedar Park, Leander, and beyond.</span>
          <span class="community-url">austinmesh.org ↗</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://houmesh.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="community-card">
          <span class="community-name">Houston Mesh</span>
          <span class="community-desc">Volunteer-run mesh community building a resilient network across the Houston metro area, using Meshtastic and MeshCore.</span>
          <span class="community-url">houmesh.com ↗</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://www.rfindex.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="community-card">
          <span class="community-name">RF Index</span>
          <span class="community-desc">Independent, side-by-side comparisons of mesh networking hardware — firsthand VSWR test results and antenna sweep charts, plus specs and pricing for Meshtastic and MeshCore devices.</span>
          <span class="community-url">rfindex.com ↗</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://meshcoretx.net/meshes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="community-card">
          <span class="community-name">MeshCore TX</span>
          <span class="community-desc">Texas-wide MeshCore mesh directory and community resource.</span>
          <span class="community-url">meshcoretx.net ↗</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://meshmap.me/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="community-card">
          <span class="community-name">Mesh Directory</span>
          <span class="community-desc">Directory of LoRa mesh communities, groups, and clubs across the US.</span>
          <span class="community-url">meshmap.me ↗</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section" id="other-regions">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Working With Other Regions</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>We built this as regional infrastructure, not a one-off personal project — and we'd rather see more of Texas (and neighboring communities) covered than keep it to ourselves. If you're running or organizing a MeshCore community in another region, we're open to giving your nodes access to our broker so you can stand up your own independently-branded map without having to run MQTT infrastructure of your own.</p>
        <p>You don't need to be organizing a whole community to reach out, either — the broker only accepts devices tagged with a pre-approved region code, so if your city or area isn't in the <a href="/connect">Connect</a> section's list yet, that's reason enough to get in touch on your own, solo node or not. Adding a region code is a small, quick change on our end.</p>
        <p>This isn't automatic — we review each request so the network stays healthy and regionally organized — but it's a quick process. Note that this is about observer infrastructure specifically (the piece that forwards packet data to a broker), not a requirement for every node on your mesh — see <a href="/connect">Connect</a> for what that setup looks like.</p>

        <h3>If you're interested, get in touch and let us know:</h3>
      </div>

      <div class="request-cards">
        <div class="request-card">
          <span class="field-label">Who You Are</span>
          <p>Your name and group/community name (if any).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="request-card">
          <span class="field-label">Your Community</span>
          <p>A link to your community's site or social presence.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="request-card">
          <span class="field-label">Contact</span>
          <p>Email address (or Discord handle).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="request-card">
          <span class="field-label">Coverage</span>
          <p>What region you cover and roughly how many nodes/operators you have.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="request-card">
          <span class="field-label">Access Type</span>
          <p>Broker access only (you run your own map), or help setting up a fully independent stack.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <Callout variant="verify" icon="✓" heading="Get in touch">
        <p>Send the details above and we'll follow up to get you connected.</p>
        <a href="mailto:info@meshtexas.org" class="btn btn-secondary">Email Us ↗</a>
      </Callout>

      <Callout variant="repo-callout" icon="⚙" heading="Prefer to run your own fully independent stack?">
        <p>Our deployment is open source and written to work for any region, not just Texas.</p>
        <a href="https://github.com/anieto/meshcore-broker-stack" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn btn-secondary">View on GitHub ↗</a>
      </Callout>

      <p class="hint" style="margin-top: 20px;">MeshTexas is community-run, volunteer infrastructure. We don't guarantee uptime, and access can be adjusted or revoked if needed to keep the network healthy for everyone.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section tint" id="commitments">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Our Commitments</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>The core network is free, and always will be:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>We don't sell data.</strong> Network activity, node telemetry, anything collected on this site — none of it is sold or shared with advertisers, ever.</li>
          <li><strong>No ads.</strong> This site exists to help people get on the mesh, not to make money from it.</li>
          <li><strong>Core access stays free.</strong> Connecting a device, using the broker, the analyzer, and the map — free for individuals and community groups, no paid tier required.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>We may look for ways to fund hardware and installs for larger repeater sites down the road — grants, partnerships, sponsorships. That's about covering the real cost of physical infrastructure, not about monetizing your data or putting the network itself behind a paywall.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-section" id="ai-disclosure">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>A Note on AI</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>I use AI a lot at work, and on side projects like this one too — it's part of how I keep this running with limited time. Some of this site's code and content were developed with AI assistance, always reviewed by a person before anything goes live. As more people contribute articles through the site, the same standard applies: AI-assisted writing is fine, as long as a real person stands behind what's published.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
